        <div type="bibliography" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
                <p>
                    <bibl><ptr target="#Evangelidis1935"/>, <citedRange>259 no. 28</citedRange></bibl> (<bibl><ptr target="#IDodoneLhôte"/> <citedRange> 30</citedRange></bibl>; <bibl><ptr target="#Eidinow2007"/>, <citedRange> 86 no. 13</citedRange>)</bibl>; <bibl><ptr target="#IDodoneDVC"/> <citedRange> 1</citedRange></bibl>. </p>
            
<p>Cf.
    <bibl><ptr target="#Parker2015"/>, <citedRange>113-114 n. 18</citedRange> (on the consultation formula)</bibl>; <bibl><ptr target="#Parker2016"/>, <citedRange>78 n. 35</citedRange> (on enquiries regarding choice of wife)</bibl>.</p>
            </div>
<div type="edition" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="grc">
    <ab>
        <lb n="1"/>ἦ ἄλλαν μαστεύων;
        </ab>
  </div>
        <div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
     <p>Shall I seek another?</p>
            </div>
        <div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="es">
        <p>¿Debo buscar otra? </p>
        </div>
        <div type="commentary" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
            <p>There are two parallel inscriptions (although with a personal construction instead of a participial one) in the Dodona oracular corpus: <bibl><ptr target="#IDodoneLhôte"/> <citedRange>29</citedRange></bibl> (<foreign xml:lang="grc"> ἄλλαν μαστείι;</foreign>) and <bibl><ptr target="#IDodoneDVC"/> <citedRange>2322A</citedRange></bibl> (<foreign xml:lang="grc">ἐ͂ ἄλλαν | μαστεύ;</foreign>), which belong to the well-attested category of consultations concerning the choice of a wife (see <bibl><ptr target="#Parker2016"/>, <citedRange>78-79</citedRange>)</bibl>. For this kind of “hyper-laconic” questions, see <bibl><ptr target="#Parker2015"/></bibl>, who argues that such elliptical formulations are best understood as abbreviations of fuller alternative questions.</p>
            
            <p n="Ithaca results">Ithaca ranks Epirus as the most likely provenance (40.22% probability), followed by Ionia (8.12%) and Caria (7.05%). Chronologically, the highest probability falls around 340-330 BC, although the model assigns broadly comparable probabilities across much of the fourth century BC. See <ref target="https://dodonaonline.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/IDodoneOnline1_2026_06_29.html">Ithaca results</ref> and <ref target="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/IDodone/IDodoneOnline/refs/heads/main/ithaca-results/IDodoneOnline1.md">metadata</ref>, and a snapshot of the <ref target="https://dodonaonline.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/IDodoneOnline1_geographical-attribution_2026_06.jpg">geographical attribution</ref>.</p>
                </div>
        </body>
